  "game_explanation": "This game has a clear but imperfectly knowable comparative-advantage structure. Badger values RED and BLUE equally highly at $0.80 and values GREEN only at $0.50, so badger should want to give up GREEN when possible and acquire RED or BLUE. Camel values RED at $0.60, GREEN at $0.50, and BLUE at only $0.40, so camel most wants RED, is roughly neutral toward GREEN, and should be most willing to part with BLUE. Squid values BLUE at $0.60, GREEN at $0.50, and RED at only $0.20, so squid strongly prefers BLUE, is fine with GREEN, and should be very willing to part with RED. The most efficient direct pattern is therefore camel giving BLUE for RED from squid, and badger trying to obtain either RED or BLUE by paying with GREEN. However, each player only knows his own values during play, so proposals must be based on inference from acceptance behavior rather than full surplus knowledge. That creates uncertainty about which counterpart is the right target and how demanding an exchange rate can still get accepted. Because acceptance decisions are made with calculators showing exact private gains and losses, strictly loss-making offers should usually be rejected. The personas suggest camel is the most deal-ready accepter, squid is careful but highly disciplined, and badger is moderately exploratory. That makes early probing likely: badger may test whether others will accept GREEN-for-BLUE or GREEN-for-RED offers; camel may make practical offers to turn low-value BLUE into RED; squid may try to convert low-value RED into BLUE or sometimes GREEN. Across three rounds, accepted trades are most likely when they give the recipient a clear private gain and use inventory the sender can spare. Trade rates may remain somewhat conservative because proposers face two-sided screening uncertainty and cannot choose among multiple acceptors.",
