  "game_explanation": "This game is likely to revolve around the strong and asymmetric red-chip incentives. Dog values RED most at $1.00 and BLUE poorly at $0.20, butterfly values BLUE most at $0.90 and also likes RED at $0.60, while ram values GREEN most tied with modest RED at $0.40 and values BLUE very little at $0.10. Because GREEN is common value at $0.50 for everyone, it is the natural medium of exchange, but not a source of surplus by itself. The largest two-player gains come from moving RED away from ram toward dog or butterfly, and moving BLUE away from ram or dog toward butterfly. Dog should want to convert BLUE or some GREEN into RED; butterfly should want to convert RED into BLUE only if terms are favorable, but more importantly should try to acquire cheap RED from ram using GREEN; ram should often be willing to part with BLUE for almost anything and may also sell RED for GREEN at favorable ratios. The main uncertainty is informational: players know only their own values, so they must infer from observed offers who likely values what. That creates cautious probing in early turns. Persona priors suggest dog is relatively conciliatory and may make workable rather than maximally extractive offers, butterfly is disciplined and quick-deal oriented so likely to post efficient, clean offers when he sees a positive trade, and ram is exploratory and moderately patient, making him willing to test terms and accept profitable but not necessarily immediate trades. Overall, a plausible path is early probing around GREEN-for-RED, followed by butterfly successfully buying RED from ram, after which dog pushes harder to acquire remaining RED and butterfly later exploits dog's low BLUE value by offering BLUE for RED on terms dog still finds individually profitable.",
